In order to solve this problem, we need to first make a key observation.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Imagine that we have a block here that's suspended by four springs.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Now we know that in order to calculate the net force on this block,

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
we have to add up all of the forces contributed by each of these springs,

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
which is going to be four times the contribution of one spring.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.000
But it also turns out that we can actually imagine all four of these springs

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:26.000
being replaced by just one single spring with a spring constant of 4K.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:31.000
It turns out that springs when put in parallel like this, you can just add up their spring constants

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
and treated as one common spring which is a pretty nifty trick.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Now that we know this fact, we can actually just imagine all four of these springs

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
on the bottom of the car as just being one big spring with spring constant 4K

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
and now we're ready to solve for the period of oscillations.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
